rComments: I enjoyed this class quite a lot. Prof Li was enthusiastic about the texts and had good insight. His lectures sometimes drifted a bit, but I, for one, liked his lecturing style, including his personal anecdotes (that related to class material). He was encouraging and friendly to me, if a little shy (which may have been read as rudeness by some).

Prof. Li is very approachable, sincere, and enthusiastic about his teaching. I personally think he is one of the best professors I've had in my three years of university. He explains the course materials in a clear manner, and I think he grades fairly.
boring boring boring. grading is unfair. he changed my arguments when grading my paper. how stupid is that? boring stupid lame ridiculous. he made what should have been a great class a terrible one.

His syllabus for postcolonial fiction would have been good, had he taught properly. Instead, he included 3rd-year-level postcolonial theory from Norton and treated it in the lectures as though he didn't need to clarify a single thing written. And he's a moody, rude professor.
his lectures are very clearly delivered. however he is very one sided and prefers you to regurgitate his interpretation of the text.
He's cool!  He stutters and bumbles about his lecture notes, but he's really cute, really nice, and the syllabus is good.  I enjoyed him.
